<h3 id="i-finally-found-a-way-to-connect-with-that-intuition-everybody-has-been-raving-about">I finally found a way to connect with that intuition everybody has been raving about</h3>
<p>I spent my time in the Algarve rigorously simmering down. Without the usual rush of home life, work, and social engagements distracting me from what‚Äôs difficult, I learned to listen to what I deeply know to be true. Entering into that conversation, I‚Äôve become better at noticing what effect everyday life has on me: the ‚Äúrebound‚Äù, as we call it in yin yoga.</p>

<h3 id="the-design-flaw-that-neurodiversity-isnt">The design flaw that neurodiversity isn‚Äôt</h3>
<p>Another transformation this year was kickstarted by Elizabeth Filips, a London medical student and YouTuber who has shown me <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=A2sS00egAzg">how I can better organize things and, well, <em>do</em> them</a>. All of my life, I‚Äôve been known to learn quickly, think originally, and get bored easily. (This is why, as I‚Äôm writing this, I‚Äôm already playing a pretty solid Philip Glass on the piano I got a week ago, but I can‚Äôt sustain a simple tidying routine to save my life.)</p>

<p>I was never unaware of what this meant or what it‚Äôs called, but what I never <em>got</em> was how to work these traits. I always thought I was just bad at consistency. That I was to blame for it, and how I shouldn‚Äôt stop trying until I could build habits like everyone else. I‚Äôve never heard Elizabeth use the word ‚Äúneurodiversity‚Äù, but it‚Äôs refreshing to hear from someone in whom I can see myself. Thanks to what I learned from her, I spent a good portion of 2022 eagerly embracing my own learning strategies, optimizing for passion rather than consistency.</p>

<h3 id="it-may-be-valuable-to-jumpstart-a-connection-by-oversharing-but-usually-it-isnt">It may be valuable to jumpstart a connection by oversharing, but usually it isn‚Äôt</h3>
<p>In my treatment cohort were nine other women, each with a uniquely originated eating disorder. Sharing the most difficult things about our lives gave us a non-verbal language that runs on gut feelings, eyes meeting, and quiet hugs. Outside of these relationships, though, 2022 showed me the value of pacing myself, friendship-wise. New people came and went, and with the ones who stayed I shared an understanding: you can‚Äôt always jumpstart a connection by oversharing, overcommitting, overinvesting.</p>

